// =============================================================================
// Depletion Tests — What Geometric Control Actually Closes the Gap?
// =============================================================================
//
// FINDING FROM ns_alignment_weights.kleis:
//   Bounding α₁ alone is INSUFFICIENT. Even with α₁ ≤ 1/Ω (strong depletion),
//   Z3 finds blow-up scenarios. Why? Because the intermediate eigenvalue λ₂ can
//   be positive, and vorticity aligned with e₂ still gets stretched.
//
// ANALYSIS:
//   S = Ω · σ_eff  where σ_eff = λ₁α₁ + λ₂α₂ + λ₃α₃
//   Worst case:    σ_eff ≤ λ₁ ≤ √(Ω·P)   →  S² ≤ Ω³·P  (a+b=4)
//   Intermediate:  σ_eff ≤ λ₂ ≤ √(Ω·P)   →  S² ≤ Ω³·P  (same!)
//
//   So controlling α₁ but not σ_eff doesn't reduce the exponent sum.
//   The real question: what bound on σ_eff closes the gap?
//
// Paper 1 showed: S² ≤ Ω·P (i.e., σ_eff² ≤ 1/Ω) gives UNSAT.
// That's a+b = 2. We need to find what geometric conditions imply it.
//
// TESTS ARE IN SEPARATE FILES (Kleis loads all structures per file):
//   ns_depletion_d1.kleis — σ_eff² ≤ P/Ω (a+b=2, expect UNSAT)
//   ns_depletion_d2.kleis — σ_eff² ≤ P   (a+b=3, expect SAT)
//   ns_depletion_d3.kleis — σ_eff² ≤ P/√Ω (a+b=5/2, expect ?)
//   ns_depletion_d4.kleis — combined α₁+biaxial (expect UNSAT?)
//   ns_depletion_d5.kleis — isotropic (expect UNSAT)
//   ns_depletion_d6.kleis — exponent scan a+b = 2.5, 2.25, 2.1, 2.0
//
// Run all: for f in theories/ns_depletion_d*.kleis; do kleis test "$f"; done
